{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519616"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:13:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:13:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13053"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13053"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.05,0.17,0.05,0.66]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5490"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103641"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5490"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13053"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86058"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"176"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1186"},{"type":"tags","id":"1989"},{"type":"tags","id":"1993"},{"type":"tags","id":"2943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4066"},{"type":"tags","id":"4847"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"},{"type":"tags","id":"13209"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9324"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14524"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17247"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17563"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36926"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49924"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103641"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the emergency department with right arm pain. Two days ago, he fell while weeding the garden, resulting in immediate pain in his right arm. It has not improved, so he attended the emergency department. He has also experienced worsening back pain and constipation over the last six months. He has had no pain elsewhere. His daughter reports he is more forgetful than usual. He has a history of prostate cancer treated with surgery five years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he has tenderness along his right humerus, with significantly reduced range of motion at his right shoulder. His right arm is neurovascularly intact distally. He has tenderness of his lumbar spine, worse on the right, but preserved range of motion. His lower limb neurological examination is unremarkable. His abdominal examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn X-ray of his right humerus shows a fracture line through some lytic areas in the metaphysis and diaphysis. An X-ray of his lumbar spine shows several small lytic lesions in the vertebral bodies. An abdominal X-ray demonstrates faecal loading. He has no leg oedema. His laboratory results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 91 g/l (132-172)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 70 \u00b5mol/l (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea 4.1 mmol/L (3.0-8.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean Corpuscular Volume 90fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet Count 159 x 10^9/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 137 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 4.1 mmol/L (3.5-5.1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChloride 107 mmol/L (98-107)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate 24 mmol/L (22-30)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlucose 4.9 mmol/L (3.9-5.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcium 2.85 mmol/L (2.15-2.55)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the patient\u0027s current symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bone marrow failure","Spinal cord compression","Paraneoplastic syndrome","Amyloidosis","Metastatic spread"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s history of back and humerus pain, constipation, confusion, and radiographic findings of lytic lesions in the bones, the most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic spread\u003C/strong\u003E of prostate cancer. Whilst most metastatic bone disease in carcinoma of the prostate is sclerotic, lytic lesions do occur. Prostate cancer commonly metastasises to bone, and the presence of lytic lesions in both the humerus and lumbar spine, along with the patient\u0027s history of prostate cancer, supports this diagnosis. The laboratory findings of anaemia and hypercalcaemia further suggest bone involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to denote that, while multiple myeloma could also present with lytic bone lesions, anaemia, and hypercalcaemia, it is less likely in this case due to the patient\u0027s history of prostate cancer and the typical presentation of prostate cancer metastasis. Multiple myeloma would more commonly present with renal impairment and a monoclonal protein spike, which are not indicated in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInfiltration and replacement of normal bone marrow cells by multiple myeloma cells can lead to \u003Cstrong\u003Ebone marrow failure\u003C/strong\u003E. While the patient does have anaemia, which could suggest bone marrow failure, the presence of lytic lesions in multiple bones suggests a more systemic issue rather than isolated bone marrow failure. Bone marrow failure typically presents with pancytopaenia causing symptoms such as bleeding, bruising, or frequent infections, which are not prominent in this case. Myeloma usually causes anaemia before progressing to pancytopaenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with right arm pain, worsening back pain, tenderness along the lumbar spine, and constipation. While spinal cord compression can lead to neurological deficits such as weakness, sensory changes, and bowel or bladder dysfunction, the constellation of symptoms in this case is not strongly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Espinal cord compression\u003C/strong\u003E. The lower limb neurological examination is unremarkable, and constipation alone is not sufficient to strongly suggest spinal cord compression. Therefore, while spinal cord compression is a possibility, it is not the most likely complication in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParaneoplastic syndromes\u003C/strong\u003E are rare disorders with complex systemic clinical manifestations from an occult malignancy causing an altered immune system. These syndromes can affect various organ systems and present with a wide range of symptoms. While paraneoplastic syndromes can manifest with neurological symptoms and cognitive changes, they are usually associated with specific types of cancer and may not fully explain the skeletal involvement and constipation seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmyloidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a group of rare conditions where a protein called amyloid builds up in your body. While amyloidosis can be a complication of multiple myeloma (MM), it typically presents with symptoms such as fatigue, weight loss, peripheral neuropathy, and symptoms related to organ dysfunction (e.g., heart, kidneys). However, in this case, the patient\u0027s acute presentation with right arm pain, back pain, and constipation, along with the findings of lytic lesions on imaging, are more indicative of active bone disease from MM rather than amyloidosis. Additionally, amyloidosis usually develops over a longer period and is less likely to present acutely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metastatic spread of prostate cancer commonly involves the bones, leading to lytic lesions, pain, and hypercalcaemia.","Lytic bone lesions, anaemia, and hypercalcaemia in a patient with a history of prostate cancer suggest metastatic disease."],"references":["Ziu E, Viswanathan VK, Mesfin FB. Spinal Metastasis. [Updated 2022 Aug 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441950/","Subramanian S, Viswanathan VK. Lytic Bone Lesions. 2022 Oct 22. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30969659.","Subramanian S, Viswanathan VK. Lytic Bone Lesions. [Updated 2022 Oct 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539837/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86058"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13053"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86058"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-25T08:32:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-25T08:33:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5490"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103641"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"typ